  "question": "The Bertsch parameter ξ quantifies the ground-state energy reduction in unitary Fermi gases compared to non-interacting Fermi gases. It serves as a fundamental benchmark for validating quantum many-body methods in strongly correlated systems. AGPs FermiNet leverages neural network wave functions with antisymmetrized geminal power singlet configurations, while FNDMC employs fixed-node diffusion Monte Carlo with trial wave functions to control fermionic sign errors. Comparing these methods at N=38 tests their accuracy in medium-sized systems where quantum fluctuations dominate. AGPs FermiNet uses VMC optimization of neural network parameters with backflow transformations to capture pairing correlations. FNDMC applies diffusion Monte Carlo with fixed-node constraints using Slater-Jastrow trial wave functions. Both methods compute total energy in EFG units, with ξ derived as the ratio to non-interacting Fermi gas energy. Error analysis incorporates Monte Carlo statistical uncertainties and finite-size scaling effects. System-specific validation against experimental ξ values ensures methodological robustness. For a unitary Fermi gas (UFG) system with N=38 particles, what is the ratio of the Bertsch parameter ξ calculated using AGPs FermiNet to that from FNDMC, as derived from the first image and the second image data? Provide the numerical value with three decimal places.",
